Those exceptione which have only the weaker effect, though they prevent the creditor from succeeding in an action, yet leave the obligatio subsisting naturaliter, with all or most os the incidente which characterise such relations (Excursus V inl). As a general rule every exceptio will have the stronger efficacy is based upon the ius gentium and natural equity: ‘desinit debitor esse is, qui nactus est exceptionem iustam nec ab aequitate naturali abhorrentem’ Dig. 50. 17. 66.

Thus the distinction between extinction ipso iure, and invalidation ope exceptionis, is not one of degree, for some exceptions produce an effect undistinguishable from extinction; it consists in the mode oi their operation. A right extinguished ipso iure can never recover its vitality; but, given an event which operates only ope exceptionis, ie. consensa countervailing right on the debtor, the obligatio still subsists, and should the debtor’s right be itsell destroyed, will once more become enforceable, and recover its original value.
